snippet.textDisplay: Someone please help me out here! I'm usually a very harsh critic, I thought both Black Panther and Guardians of the Galaxy 2 were trash. Most of my favorite movies are non-fantasy dramas like Lost in Translation or 21 Grams, and still I don't see how this movie was THAT bad. I haven't seen the other movies in the franchise more than maybe five times each (excluding the last two), so I'm not an expert on the subject. Can someone tell me what those gigantic plot holes were and why no one is talking about the wonderful use of animatronics as compared to the CG-heavy The Last Jedi? It's far from my favorite movie of the year and doesn't reach the heights of the original trilogy, but apart from episode 3 I felt that this was clearly on par with - or better than - the other installments in the saga. Just someone please calmly explain what it was that went over my head that completely ruined this movie. I want to understand!

snippet.textDisplay: Ascribing the makeup of the film to fear of letting down fans is a pretty hefty inference to make based on a single viewing with no actual insight into the production. I’m not sensing a lot of respect for the gargantuan achievement of tying the saga up as well as it did, and it did. This isn’t an intellectual exercise. The film is meant to evoke strong emotions, even more so because of its space opera genre. I think if films were criticised like this when the original trilogy was released they never would have achieved their mythical status. Thankfully box office numbers are going to prove this one of the most successful film outings ever, and rightfully so.

snippet.textDisplay:
...At least this movie was a FUN rollercoaster ride with Star Wars action, visuals and sounds. Like it should be! The special FX are absolutely well done! It is fun and entertaining IMHO. ...And yes, there are plot holes the size of a Death Star, but that is a Star Wars standard. ;) I know it is hard for some people to see past these plot holes, because they lack the imagination to fill them in for themselves or they want a story to be serviced to them, told perfectly from A to Z and all things tied together. Which to me sounds like a boring movie and more of a documentary, but that depends on your character, I guess. ;)
Nevertheless I am very happy it was not as boring as f*&% and bad as The Last Jedi! ...And hey! ...Look at it from the bright side! We now know why Leia can do a 'Mary Poppins'. ;)

So, to me a 7/10 sounds right. My 12yr old son thinks it is a 10/10. He enjoyed it very much!
